<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-08T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-08T03:00:00-05:00" n="869" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d869">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11526: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-08T16:00:00+08:00">December 8, 1937—4
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 8—9:41 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>23. A representative of a foreign Embassy stated this morning that a
                                few days ago 42 Soviet planes arrived in Nanchang bringing about 100
                                Soviet flyers and other aviation personnel, also that about 50
                                Soviet flyers are in Hankow and a number of planes including an
                                efficient pursuit plane. This information has not been confirmed but
                                is regarded as probably reliable.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Shanghai, Nanking, Peiping.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>